\section{Monetary Matters}
d11 28
a38 23
the various goods produced by craftsmen by the Goods List (see Players
Handbook).  Weaponsmiths' products are valued on the Weapons Table
(\S\ref{tables:weapons}); Armourers' on the Armour and Shield Tables
(\S\ref{tables:armour} and \S\ref{tables:shields}).  The three factors
which determine the price of finished goods are the quality of the
material used, the hours spent in construction, and the estimated Rank
of the artisan (if one person produces the goods) or of the overseer
(if the effort is a team project).  However, if a character wishes to
purchase a custom-made or rare item, then they will have to negotiate
with the artisan (represented by the GM), and may defray by providing
some of the scarcer components themself.  The barter system is
acceptable when dealing in costly or rare items.

\subsubsection{The value of a coin is determined by its weight and metal
of which it is made.}

\begin{tabular}{l@@{\hspace{0.5em}}c@@{\hspace{1.0em}}l}
\textbf{Name} & \textbf{Weight} & \textbf{Value} \\
Copper farthing (cf) & 1/5 oz & \\
Silver penny (sp) & 1/20 oz & 4 cf \\
Gold shilling (gs) & 1/20 oz & 12 sp \\
Truesilver guinea (tg) & 1/10 oz & 21 gs \\
\end{tabular}
d40 2
a41 3
Other common coins include the halfpenny, threepence, and sixpence.
The values and weights of these coins correspond to those of the
Silver Penny.
d43 6
a48 1
\section{Health and Fitness}
d50 3
a52 1
\subsubsection{Grievous Damage}
d54 3
a56 57
Grievous damage is damage that is inflicted is specified on the
grievous injury table.  It can only be healed once the wound
associated with it has been healed (For example if one had an ear
sliced off for 2 extra Endurance damage then those 2 Endurance could
not be healed until the ear had been regenerated).  Even if the wound
is such that extra repair or regeneration is not necessary (for
example concussion), a healer is required to heal the Endurance points
(that is a healing potion or spell is not sufficient).

\subsubsection{Field Operations}

Once a healer begins work on curing a patient the condition of the
patient is ``stabilised'' while that curing is continuing.  This means
that no Endurance or Fatigue loss will occur for the condition that is
being cured.  Other afflictions will be unaffected.  After each
healing attempt a pulse effectively passed prior to any other attempt
being begun.

\subsubsection{Below Zero Endurance}

When a character is below zero Endurance they are on the very brink of
death.  They will continue to take damage from any further blows,
spells, grievous wounds which are bleeders, burning, etc. and in any
case will lose 1 Fatigue (Endurance when Fatigue is exhausted) per
pulse due to blood loss and system failure.  They will not die
however until their Endurance falls below negative one-half their
\emph{original} Endurance.  If they can be healed to at least 0
Endurance before this occurs then they will not die.  The Endurance
can be cured via magic (for example Celestial or Mind Mage healing,
Mind Mage Empathy) or the arts of a healer (Rank 3 -- Heal Endurance).

The entity cannot drink a healing potion but one can be massaged down
their throat.  The chance of doing this is equal to the Manual
Dexterity + Perception of the person administering the potion, or if a
healer, 90 + Healer Rank.  If successful then D10 per 10 points of the
healing potion's curing (round down) will be received.  If the person
fails the roll, the potion is wasted, but no harmful effects occur to
the patient.

GMs should not let players take advantage of out of character
information when another player's character is below 0 Endurance.  A
visual and tactile examination of the entity will reveal that the
entity is dead.  A successful DA or empathy will reveal the actual
state of the entity.  (Remember that all skills have a maximum of (90
+ Rank)\% chance of being successful, even if they have no stated base
chance).

\subsection{Recuperation}
\label{recuperation}

\subsubsection{The rate at which Endurance Points are recovered depends
on how active the injured being is.}

If a being expends and/or loses no more than one-half their Fatigue
Points (round down) for three consecutive days, they regain one
Endurance Point at the end of the third day.  Otherwise, they recover
an Endurance Point at the end of the following (\ie fourth) day.
d58 3
a60 2
If a being is given ministrations from a physicker's kit, their body
requires one less day to regain an Endurance Point.
d62 3
a64 8
\subsubsection{Injuries which are not quantified as Endurance Point
losses (\eg hamstrung muscles) heal at the same rate as they do in
this world.}

The GM should assume that an Endurance value of 15 indicates a body
which heals in average time.  Values greater than 15 will allow a
being to heal more quickly, while values lower than 15 will cause a
corresponding extension to the time required.
d66 4
a69 2
\subsection{Eating and Drinking}
\label{eating}
d71 2
a72 1
\subsubsection{Requirements}
d74 2
d77 3
a79 3
factors.  These include the person (endurance, weight, build,
metabolic rate and race); the activity (light, medium, hard or
strenuous) and the environment or terrain.
d81 1
a81 1
On average 1lb of food and 2 pints of water per day is required.
d83 1
d85 2
a86 1
\subsubsection{Starvation}
d88 3
a90 3
\begin{Description}
\item[Starvation occurs] when a character does not have at least 1
nourishing meal a day.
d92 2
a93 8
\item[Effects of starvation] the character will have their Fatigue
maximum and Endurance temporarily reduced by 1 each day.  This
decrease will last until the character starts receiving proper
nourishment.

\item[Recovery] a starved character's Fatigue maximum and Endurance
will recover by 1 point each day, after the first, that they receive
proper nourishment.
d95 1
a95 1
\end{Description}
d97 3
a99 1
\subsubsection{Dehydration}
d101 6
a106 1
\begin{Description}
d108 3
a110 14
\item[Dehydration occurs] when a character does not have at least 2
pints of water a day.  This will increase in high temperatures, +1
pint per 10 degrees above 20.

\item[Effects of dehydration] the character will have their Fatigue
maximum and Endurance temporarily reduced by 5 each day.  If the
character receives part of their water requirement, the penalty is
reduced.  For every 20\% (or fraction) less than the daily requirement
they lose 1 from FT max and EN.  This decrease will last until the
character starts receiving adequate quantities of water.

\item[Recovery] a dehydrated character's Fatigue maximum and Endurance
will recover by 5 points each day, after the first, that they receive
adequate quantities of water.
d112 1
a112 1
\end{Description}
d114 4
a117 2
\subsection{Fatigue Loss and Recovery}
\label{adventure:fatigue}
d119 4
a122 5
Characters have a tendency to lose Fatigue Points in the course of
adventures.  A fatigued character must engage in some restful action
to recover lost Fatigue Points.  Sleep, as might be expected, is the
best way to become refreshed, but there are several other options
available to the character who wishes to remain alert.
d124 1
a124 2
\subsubsection{The rate at which a character loses Fatigue Points is
determined by how tiring their main activity for each hour is.}
d126 2
d129 1
a129 3
A character can lose Fatigue Points when they engage in any activity
more stressful than a leisurely walk.  There are four classes of
activity which can fatigue a character:
d141 1
a141 1
labor, etc.
d149 16
a164 18
It is possible for a character to achieve a level of performance more
taxing than Strenuous Exercise, which requires superhuman exertion.
This type of activity is governed by the GM, who will have to
determine how many Fatigue Points are lost by a character conducting
such actions.

A character's degree of exertion is judged each hour.  Since a
character does not necessarily choose to do the same activity for an
entire hour, the GM must average out the levels of activity achieved
at different times within the hour.  If the GM is consistent with
their guidelines for what type of activity constitutes which of the
four types of exercise, the players will be able to keep a running
total of their characters' Fatigue Points without forcing the GM to
stop play to consider the matter.

\subsubsection{A character is limited in the weight they can bear; if
they engage in exercise, they may become fatigued more quickly because
of the objects they carry with them.}
d173 17
a189 25
When a creature has a Physical Strength value greater than 40, the GM
divides that value by 40.  Multiply the quotient by the entry for
40, and add the entry corresponding to the remainder to determine that
creature's capabilities.

\subsubsection{The Fatigue Point loss for a character engaged in magic
or combat is not calculated using the provisions of this rule.}

The only Fatigue Points lost for casting magic, being affected by
magic, skills, or physical attacks are those lost per the appropriate
rules (\ie the deductions for casting, using skills, or being
successfully struck).

\subsubsection{The Fatigue Point loss rates given in these rules assume
that the character is in good health and is well fed.}

If the character is not in condition, the GM should shift up Physical
Strength rows and / or shift weight columns to represent debilitating
effects upon the character.  The shift of weight columns should also
be accompanied by a corresponding decrease in the maximum weight
allowable for that character.

\subsubsection{The Fatigue status of a character need be calculated
only before they enter into combat or wish to perform magic or, if
they do neither, once for the entire day.}
d191 4
a194 1
\textbf{Procedure}
d205 2
a206 3
Multiply the resulting number (Fatigue Points lost per hour) by the
number of hours during which all three factors (Physical Strength,
weight carried and rate of exercise) remain constant.
d213 2
a214 2
Add each separate product (\ie subtotal) to determine the total
Fatigue Points expended by the character so far.
d217 17
a233 15
If a character's Fatigue Point total is reduced below zero, they are
exhausted (see below). Their Fatigue is considered zero, if they
should become involved in combat.

\subsubsection{An exhausted character is limited in the activities they
may choose to do, and is worse in the performance of their abilities.}

A character may choose to exert themselves after their Fatigue Points
are reduced to zero for a period during which they would normally
expend (if they had them) one-half their initial Fatigue Points (round
down).  Unless they succeed in a Willpower Check every (2 \x
Endurance) minutes, they will collapse if they reach or try to exceed
this limit.  An exhausted character must sleep for as much time as
they was performing at least light exercise while exhausted
\emph{before} they may recover \emph{any} Fatigue Points.
d236 8
a243 1
must succeed in a separate Willpower Check.
d245 14
a258 20
Add \emph{one} for each half-hour (or fraction thereof) that a
character has been exhausted to any percentile roll to resolve the use
of one of that character's abilities (\eg to strike a blow during
combat).

\subsubsection{A character may regain Fatigue Points by resting or
eating a hot meal.}

A character may never have a Fatigue Point total greater than their
Fatigue value.

A character recovers Fatigue Points according to the following
schedule:

\begin{tabular}{lr}
\textbf{Activity} & \textbf{Fatigue Points / Hour} \\
Relaxation      & 1 \\
Nap             & 2 \\
Sleep           & 3 \\
Eat Hot Meal    & 2 \\
d260 1
d264 1
a264 1
during a 24 hour period, and each time must be separated by at least 4
d268 6
d275 3
a277 4
Fatigue Point less per hour or meal, and if their Endurance is less
than 5, they recover one less Fatigue Point.  However, a character
must always recover a minimum of one-half a Fatigue Point when
resting.
d281 3
a283 3
additional one-half of a Fatigue Point per hour or meal.  Each
succeeding ten point Endurance bracket carries an additional one-half
Fatigue Point per hour or meal bonus.
d286 2
a287 5
A character that does not get at least 6 hours of rest and/or sleep
per day, will have their Fatigue maximum temporarily reduced by 1 FT
per hour (or fraction) of sleep under 6.  This may be recovered at the
rate of 1 FT per 4 hours sleep.

d290 1
a290 2
\subsubsection{The weight borne by a character may temporarily reduce a
character's Agility.}
d292 27
a318 1
\textbf{Procedure:}
d320 1
a320 1
\begin{Enumerate}
d322 3
a324 2
\item Cross-reference the character's Physical Strength and the weight
they are carrying.
d326 1
a326 2
\item Read down this column until it intersects with the row which
reads ``Agility Loss.''
d328 3
a330 8
\item Deduct the resulting number from the character's Agility until
there is a change in the weight they bear (at which point the
subtraction must be recalculated).

\item A character is considered to have a minimum Agility of 1 for all
other game functions.  The character's current Agility is used as a
basis for determining their current TMR.
\end{Enumerate}
d332 1
a332 1
\subsection{Recovery from Damage}
d334 2
a335 4
\subsubsection{Endurance recovery}

There are many causes of a character taking Endurance damage.
However, once damaged there are two primary methods of recovering.
d337 2
a338 1
\begin{Description}
d340 3
a342 5
\item[Natural healing] A character will recover 1 Endurance for every
three full days of rest.  The recuperation will be ineffective and
interrupted if the character:
\begin{itemize}
\item takes any further EN damage
d344 2
a345 2
\item does not receive adequate nourishment (\S\ref{eating}).
\end{itemize}
d347 2
a348 3
\item[Being healed] Healers, herbalists, and some magics may aid the
recovery of Endurance.  The exact effects can be found under the
appropriate skill or magic.
d350 17
a366 1
\end{Description}
d370 4
a373 3
Endurance loss resulting from Specific Grievous injuries may not be
healed normally.  The specific injury must be healed, then the
Endurance may be recovered.
d377 3
a379 3
Many injuries will not heal naturally.  The following states which
injuries will heal, and how long it will take.

d381 1
a381 1
\item[Broken bones] Will knit in 4 weeks for a simple fracture, or up
d385 11
a395 12
\item[Internal injuries] A character will usually die from internal
injuries.  If the character is comfortable, unmoving, and kept alive
by a healer or physician, internal injuries will heal 1 Endurance
point per week.

\item[Open wounds] Will heal at half the normal rate, provided that
they are kept free of infection.  Open wounds will leave scars.

\item[Removed body parts] Will not regrow naturally.  However, they
will heal over at quarter the normal rate, provided they are kept free
from infection.

d398 3
a400 5
\subsubsection{Magical healing of Specific Injuries}

Healers and certain magics may heal specific injuries.  The time taken
and effects of these magics may be found under the appropriate skill
or magic.
d404 3
a406 1
\label{infection}
d408 2
a409 3
If a character is wounded there is the possibility that they have
become infected as a result of their wounds.  An Infection Check must
be performed to determine whether they are infected or not.
d413 1
a413 1
The chance of becoming infected depends on the entities health, the
d415 1
a415 1
cumulative but only one from each category.
d432 1
a432 1
Specific grievous injuries may also increase the chance of infection.
d436 4
a439 3
An entity with an infection will be slowly poisoned by the infection.
The damage is [D-5] Endurance per day, until the infection is cured.
An infected wound may not be healed until the infection is cured.
d443 2
a444 2
There are two ways to recover from infection.  The first is to tough
it out.  The second is to be healed by a healer.
d447 2
a448 2
\item[Toughing it out] An infected character may make a roll (Base
Chance of Endurance \%) every day to recover naturally.
d451 2
a452 2
Healer or by magic.  The rank at which this is possible, and the
chance of success can be found under the appropriate skill or spell.
